Theoretically Principled Federated Learning for Balancing Privacy and Utility

Xiaojin Zhang1Â Â  Wenjie Li2Â Â  Kai Chen1 Â Â  Shu-Tao Xia2,4 Â Â  Qiang Yang1,3,

Abstract

We propose a general learning framework for the protection mechanisms that protects privacy via distorting model parameters, which facilitates the trade-off between privacy and utility. The algorithm is applicable to arbitrary privacy measurements that maps from the distortion to a real value. It can achieve personalized utility-privacy trade-off for each model parameter, on each client, at each communication round in federated learning. Such adaptive and fine-grained protection can improve the effectiveness of privacy-preserved federated learning. Theoretically, we show that gap between the utility loss of the protection hyperparameter output by our algorithm and that of the optimal protection hyperparameter is sub-linear in the total number of iterations. The sublinearity of our algorithm indicates that the average gap between the performance of our algorithm and that of the optimal performance goes to zero when the number of iterations goes to infinity. Further, we provide the convergence rate of our proposed algorithm. We conduct empirical results on benchmark datasets to verify that our method achieves better utility than the baseline methods under the same privacy budget.

1 Introduction

The rapid expansion of large-scale datasets has sparked a demand for distributed learning. Federated learning (FL)Â [1, 2, 3, 4] allows multiple parties to train a machine learning model collaboratively without sharing private data. In recent years, FL has achieved significant progress in developing privacy-preserving machine learning systems, especially for semi-honest adversaries who faithfully follow the federated learning protocol but may infer private information of other participants based on exposed model parameter. The statistical dependence between private data and publicly transmitted information determines the amount of information about private data that a semi-honest person can deduce from exchanged information. It was revealed that exposed gradients of learnt models could be used by semi-honest adversaries to recover private training images with pixel-level accuracy (e.g., DLG [5], Inverting Gradients [6], Improved DLG [7], GradInversion [8]), referred to as the gradient leakage attacking.

Early attempts aiming to thwart privacy attacks include homomorphic encryption (HE) [9], secure multi-party computation (MPC)Â [10, 11, 12], differential privacy (DP) Â [13], and gradient compression (GC)Â [14]. HE and MPC can protect private data without jeopardizing model performance, but they incur heavy computation and communication overhead, especially for deep neural networks. In addition, HE and MPC do not secure clientsâ€™ private data after decryption for the server aggregationÂ [15]. DP and GC protect data privacy by distorting (i.e., adding noise or compressing) shared model updates, which typically leads to significantly deteriorated model performance. To obtain the best of both worlds (i.e., privacy and performance), Â [16, 17, 18, 19] leverage fine-grained DP or regularization to mitigate the impact of noise on model performance. However, these protection mechanisms still require tedious engineering efforts to identify the optimal protection hyperparameters. In this work, we propose a novel protection mechanism that learns the distortion in tandem with the optimization of model parameters, thereby automatically achieving a satisfactory privacy-utility trade-off.

Our Contributions

First, we formulate privacy-utility trade-off as an optimization problem with regard to the hyperparameter, which aims at finding appropriate hyperparameters that minimizes the utility loss and maintains potential privacy leakage below an acceptable level simultaneously.

  • â€¢

    Privacy Measurement: Some works consider privacy measurements similar to our privacy measurements, such as information leakage [20] and Kullback-Leibler divergence [21]. [22, 23] proposed a privacy measurement in the field of federated learning, which measured the loss of privacy using the gap between the prior and posterior beliefs via Jenson-Shannon divergence. All these works assume that the prior distribution is known in advance, which is impractical in many application scenarios. In contrast, our measurement does not require knowledge on prior distribution and turns out to be very useful to design an algorithm with theoretical guarantee.

  • â€¢

    Utility Measurement: Unlike the previous work that measures utility simply using the expected distance between the original model and the distorted model [20], we measure utility loss using the model performance associated with the original model and the distorted model precisely, which directly depicts the modelâ€™s utility and makes the problem more challenging though.

  • â€¢

    Algorithm Performance Measurement: Inspired by the regret metric used in the field of learning theory ( [24, 25]), we evaluate the performance of the protection mechanism via the gap between the performance of the algorithm with the learned hyperparameter and that of the optimal hyperparameter.

Second, we propose an algorithm framework that facilitates the utility-privacy trade-off for the protection mechanisms. To capture the performance variation of the model with respect to the distortion of model parameter under the constraint on privacy leakage, we use projected gradient descent to find the hyperparameter with near-optimal model utility.

  • â€¢

    In light of privacy constraints, we provide a learning-based protection mechanism for minimizing utility loss, aiming at achieving personalized trade-off between privacy and utility for privacy-preserving federated learning. Given the privacy constraint, the amount of noise to be added is optimized instead of just adding the smallest amount of noise satisfying the privacy constraint.

  • â€¢

    We show that the distortion adopted by our algorithm is near-optimal and provide a novel theoretical analysis for the convergence of our proposed algorithm. Specifically, we show that there exists an algorithm satisfying that the utility loss of the algorithm for client kğ‘˜k at round tğ‘¡t is close to that of the optimal value subject to the constraints on privacy (TheoremÂ 5.1). As a comparison, [26] formulated the trade-off between privacy and utility as optimization problems beyond the field of federated learning. However, the optimization problems might not be tractable in practice and they only provided a closed-form solution for some special Boolean-valued special cases. Further, we show that the average squared gradient norm of our proposed algorithm is bounded, which is the first convergence result that concerns privacy-utility trade-off with general formulations to our best knowledge (TheoremÂ 5.2).

  • â€¢

    We apply our proposed algorithm framework to distinct kinds of privacy measurements, including DP and a novel measurement that evaluates the amount of privacy leaked using the gap between the estimated data and the true data separately. Empirical results conducted on benchmark datasets show that our method achieves better utility than the baseline method under the same privacy budget.

2 Related Work

Attacking and Protection Mechanisms in Federated Learning

In HFL, [27, 5, 6, 7, 8] demonstrate that adversaries could exploit gradient information to restore the private image data to pixel-level accuracy, with distinct settings of prior distributions and conditional distributions. General protection mechanisms proposed to protect clientsâ€™ private data include Homomorphic Encryption (HE)Â [28, 29], Secure Multi-Party Computation (MPC)Â [10, 11, 12], Differential Privacy (DP)Â [30, 31, 13], and Gradient Compression (GC) [32]. Although these protection mechanisms can protect data privacy, HE and MPC impose a huge burden on computation and communication, while DP and GC suffer from deteriorated model performance. Thus, a lot of effort has been made to preserve data privacy and maintain model performance simultaneously. For example, [16, 17] adopt record-level client DP and [18] allocates layer-wise noise to save superfluous privacy budget; [19] leverages a perturbation regularizer to limit the impact of the noise on the model performance; Â [33] utilizes split learning to protect privacy and exploits generative neural network to compensate performance loss.

Privacy-Utility Trade-off

The optimal privacy-utility trade-off in federated learning is cast as a constrained optimization problem in which the utility loss is minimized subject to a predefined constraint for privacy leakage ([23]). [20] modeled non-asymptotic privacy guarantees in terms of the inference cost gain achieved by an adversary through the released output. [34] exhibited tradeoffs between privacy and convergence rate in the locally private settings. [26] illustrated that the optimal utility-privacy trade-off can be solved using a standard linear programming, but the closed-form solution was only provided for the special binary case. [35, 36, 37] provided asymptotic results on the rate-distortion-equivocation region with an increasing number of sampled data. [37] quantified utility via accuracy, and privacy via entropy. They provided a utility-privacy tradeoff region for i.i.d. data sources with known distribution based on rate-distortion theory. They left the problem of quantifying utility-privacy tradeoffs for more general sources as a challenging open problem. [38] measured distortion using the expected Hamming distance between the input and output databases, and measured privacy leakage using identifiability, differential privacy, and mutual-information privacy separately. The relation between these distinct privacy measurements was established under a unified privacy-distortion framework. [39] provided a trade-off when utility and privacy were both evaluated using Ï‡2superscriptğœ’2\chi^{2}-based information measures.

We consider the server is a semi-honest adversary, who faithfully follows the federated training protocol, yet may mount gradient inversionÂ [27] attacks to reconstruct the private data of participating clients upon observing the shared model updates.

Privacy Leakage

In this work, we use two measurements for privacy leakage. One is the commonly used differential privacy, which depends on the predefined distribution, therefore we call it distribution-dependent privacy measurement. The other measurement is related to the distortion extent (Eq. (2)), which does not rely on the distribution, therefore we call it distribution-independent privacy measurement. For the first measurement, please refer to section III of [18]. Now we introduce the second measurement in detail. The privacy leakage is measured based on the gap between the dataset estimated by an attacker and the original dataset. The semi-honest attacker uses an optimization algorithm [5, 6, 7, 8] to reconstruct the original dataset dğ‘‘d of the client given the exposed model information Wğ‘ŠW. Given the privacy budget, the optimization problem aims at deriving the value of the hyperparameter for trading-off utility and privacy. Note that for the distribution-independent protection mechanism, the hyperparameter itself depicts the protection mechanism. For distribution-dependent protection mechanisms such as Laplacian mechanism and Gaussian mechanism, the hyperparameter together with the predefined distribution depict the protection mechanism. The optimization problem defined in Eq. (13) is not guaranteed to be convex. It is possibly intractable and has no close-form solutions. We propose an adaptive learning algorithm to solve the optimization problem (Eq. (13)) in SectionÂ 5.

5 Algorithm for Balancing Privacy and Utility

5.2 The Algorithm

The main algorithm is presented in AlgorithmÂ 1, which contains two subroutines AlgorithmÂ 2 and AlgorithmÂ 3. The inputs of our algorithm include privacy budget for client kğ‘˜k at round tğ‘¡t (denoted as Ï‡t(k)subscriptsuperscriptğœ’ğ‘˜ğ‘¡\chi^{(k)}_{t}), functions g(k)superscriptğ‘”ğ‘˜g^{(k)} and â„’(k)superscriptâ„’ğ‘˜\mathcal{L}^{(k)}. With the measurements for privacy and utility, we can define g(k)superscriptğ‘”ğ‘˜g^{(k)} and â„’(k)superscriptâ„’ğ‘˜\mathcal{L}^{(k)} accordingly. g(k)superscriptğ‘”ğ‘˜g^{(k)} outputs a lower bound for the hyperparameter given the privacy budget, and â„’(k)superscriptâ„’ğ‘˜\mathcal{L}^{(k)} is designed according to the mapping from the hyperparameter to utility (two specific forms of g(k)superscriptğ‘”ğ‘˜g^{(k)} and â„’(k)superscriptâ„’ğ‘˜\mathcal{L}^{(k)} are illustrated in ExampleÂ 5.1 and ExampleÂ 5.2). AlgorithmÂ 2 follows the traditional design of federated learning algorithms ([2]) and updates model parameters via gradient descent.

AlgorithmÂ 3 executes a learning algorithm for a total of Mğ‘€M rounds. The output of AlgorithmÂ 3 leads to an optional distortion set based on the measurement of privacy leakage. Then, we conduct efficient constrained optimization via projected gradient descent to minimize the objective function on the optional distortion set.

6 Experiments

6.1 Experiment Setup

We conducted experiments on MNIST and Fashion-MNIST to evaluate the effectiveness of our general distortion learning algorithm. The detailed federated training setting and attack setting is shown in Appendix. The experiments are designed to answer the following research questions. Q1: Does the proposed method achieves better utility-privacy trade-off than static methods Q2: Does the proposed method performs consistently under different privacy measures?

Defense Setting

We set up defense methods for both distribution-independent (e.g. Eq(20)) and distribution-dependent (e.g. Eq(22)) mechanism to validate the effectiveness of our algorithm under distinct privacy leakage measurement. They are compared in identical FL setting and attack setting. Under each privacy framework, we set up a degraded version of our algorithm using traditional static distortion strategy as the baseline. The total 4 defense methods are listed below:

  • â€¢

    PL-Learn: The complete version of AlgorithmÂ 3 with our Privacy Leakage definition. For each model parameter, the distortion noise is dynamically adapted in the range of [l(k),u(k)]superscriptğ‘™ğ‘˜superscriptğ‘¢ğ‘˜[l^{(k)},u^{(k)}] by our optimization algorithm. Adam optimizer is used for distortion learning.

  • â€¢

    PL-Identical: The degraded version of PL-Learn, a random noise with lower-bound noise extent (decided by l(k)superscriptğ‘™ğ‘˜l^{(k)} in AlgorithmÂ 3) is uniformly applied to each model parameter, without any optimization stepped. The word â€œIdenticalâ€ means the noise extent applied to each parameter is identical, which is the most common strategy.

  • â€¢

    DP-Learn: The complete version of AlgorithmÂ 3 with DP-Laplacian protection mechanism. the algorithm optimizes the randomly sampled noise to achieve better privacy-utility trade-off.

  • â€¢

    DP-Identical: It is the degraded version of DP-Learn, similar to PL-Identical.

Evaluation Setting

The test accuracy of global model is used as utility metric. For each privacy framework, we set progressive budget values and evaluate utility of defense methods. Thus, the algorithm is considered to maintains better trade-off when it achieves better utility performance under the same budget level. To empirically evaluate the privacy protection effect of defense mechanisms, we also use MSE and SSIM to assess the quality of DLG-recovered images. In addition, we leverage Calibrated Averaged Performance (CAP)[44] to quantify the trade-off between main task accuracy and data recovery error (definition shown in Appendix).

6.2 Results and Analysis

Better Privacy-Utility Trade-off

Figure 1 show the privacy-utility tradeoff curve under different privacy framework and defense mechanisms. We observe that 1) Our method consistently achieves better accuracy than baseline methods in all cases with same privacy budget. 2) Our method performs better as the budget values becomes smaller (the protection strength becomes more strict). As shown in Table 1, The performance gain increases from a moderate value of 1.36%percent1.361.36\%(Ïµ=800italic-Ïµ800\epsilon=800) to a significant large value of 8.48%percent8.488.48\%(Ïµ=200italic-Ïµ200\epsilon=200) on MNIST dataset. 3) Our method is more robust to extremely large distortion. when Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon gets further small to be 606060 (which means more noise are added to model), the distortion noise gets enough large to destroy the training of baseline method, which only have 8.92%percent8.928.92\% accuracy and is worse than random guess. While our method is still available and achieves 51.04%percent51.0451.04\% accuracy. Thus we answered Q1 and Q2.

Maintained Empirical Defense Effect

As Table 2(a) shows, Our methodâ€™s empirical protection effect (against DLG) under a certain privacy budget is the same to baseline. That is to say, the theoretical protection extent (claimed by privacy budget) is do supported by the empirical observation (by MSE and SSIM of the reconstructed image). As more Figure in Appendix visualizes, DLG failed to reconstruct images in both methods, and reconstructed images are also very similar in visual. Table 2(b) further reports the empirical utility-privacy tradeoff against DLG attack via the CAP metric. We observe that our method achieves higher CAP value on all datasets and privacy frameworks.

Intuitive Analysis of Distortion Learning

Figure 2 shows the layer-wise distortion statistics to analysis the influence of learning process. â€œfcâ€ and â€œconvâ€ denotes for fully-connected layer and convolution layer, â€œwâ€ and â€œbâ€ denotes for weight and bias. We observe that 1) The distortion extent of some layers are significantly changed but others are not. This may intuitively explain the success of our algorithm in maintaining utility. e.g., in the left-most figure of Figure 2, the algorithm selectively amplifies(conv2.w, conv3.b), reduces(conv1.w, conv1.b, conv2.b, conv3.b) and maintains (fc.b, fc.w) the distortion extent of different layers to balance the privacy and utility. 2) The standard deviation in each layer only changes a little. This indicates that the chaos level is not changed by the algorithm, which maybe the key factor to maintain the same protection level to baselines.

Appendix A Broader Impact and Limitation

We propose a general distortion learning framework for building protection mechanisms that can achieve better trade-off between privacy and utility. Our work is expected to promote more researches on designing more utility-friendly protection machanism, thus could better address the privacy leakage threat of FL. In this paper, we mainly demonstrate the effectiveness of the overall framework and its empirical results on image classification problem. More detailed and specific design is needed to suit our framework in diverse FL scenarios and different tasks, which is the limitation of current work and also the direction of our future studies.

Appendix B Appendix for Experiments

FL Setting

To avoid the introduction of overly complex factors and evaluate the effectiveness of our framework itself, we employ a simple and straightforward FL setting for experiments. We use FedSGD as the training algorithm with full client selection, the number of local epoch and local batch are both set to 1. As a mild choice, the number of client is 4 in all experiments. For each client, there are 1K, 1.2K and 1.2K samples for train, validation and test respectively, the label distribution among all client is identical. We follow [5, 6] to use a simplified LeNet Model (denoted as â€œLeNetZhuâ€) as the backbone network. It has 3 convolution layers and 1 fully connected layer.

Attack Setting

We select the InvGrad[6] as the attacking method. As a general attack assumption for FL, the attacker is assumed to have knowledge of the weight updates [6]. We also assume the attacker has knowledge of the true label to simplify the attack. For each target batch data, 1600 attack iterations are conducted with the Adam optimizer, the attack learning rate is set to 1, and the total variation coefficient is 1e-5. Due to the weakness of DLG methods in big batch attacking, we use a small batch size 4 and local training epoch 1 to increase the vulnerability of the learning process. For each client, we select to perform attack on the first batch, at the convergent epoch.

Additional Trade-off Results

Table 5 shows the detailed quantitive results of privacy-utility trade-off under our privacy framework. Figure 3 shows the client training process under a certain budget value, showing the faster and better convergent curve of our method.

Detailed Quantitive Defense Results

To ensure that protection mechanisms achieve the expected same level protection effects against DLG attack, we further quantitively validate the MSE error and SSIM between DLG-reconstructed images and ground truth. Figure 4 visualize the defense effect at a specific budget and Table 3 and Table 4 report MSE and SSIM results on all budgets. It is observed that, the absolute SSIM under all cases is less than 6% and the mean difference under all budget values is near to zero, indicating the same-level protection effect of our method and baseline.

Implementation Details

For DP-Laplacian privacy mechanism, we use threshold C=500ğ¶500C=500 for gradient clip (a common operation for DP to bound the gradient, see more in [13, 18]). For the distortion learning process, we set learning rate Î³t=0.1subscriptğ›¾ğ‘¡0.1\gamma_{t}=0.1, iteration round M=10ğ‘€10M=10 in all cases for demonstration. Besides, we also heuristically add a small ratio of negative distortion norm as an regularization loss term to adaptively encourage the increase of distortion extent. Note that, it is flexible to use other heuristic strategies to (maybe better) fulfill the requirement of bounded distortion, our experiment choice is just for demonstration. For the common training settings, we use the same random seed sâ€‹eâ€‹eâ€‹d=1ğ‘ ğ‘’ğ‘’ğ‘‘1seed=1 and the same initialization noise (for DLG) in all experiments.
